                  +1 is evaluated with Eq. (10) from its previous velocity and from the distances between its current position and its own best position p(t

                    a
                  ) and the swarm global best g(t

                    a
                  ). This new velocity is used to move the particle and to find its new position at step t

                    a
                  +1 following Eq. (11). The swarm investigates the search space randomly but keeps the memory of the “best” decision parameters g(t

                    a
                  ) (corresponding to the minimum of the fitness function over all t

                    a
                  ) and the best decision parameter p(t

                    a
                  ) for each particle for all previous steps. Therefore, PSO is often classified as a collaborative method, the best particles p(t

                    a
                  ) and g(t

                    a
                  ) contributing equally to the next swarm (Eq. (10)). This specific aspect of the method distinguishes it from blind Monte Carlo methods [46] and from those based on the selection of the best decision parameters [43].

This basic version of PSO could also be improved by including some recent developments [47, 48, 50–52]. Some can be predicted from careful inspection of the basic pseudo-algorithm:
the termination criterion can be a function of the dispersion of the swarm or a fixed threshold of the fitness function F [46];
the boundaries of D can be modified along the evolutionary loop [46];
c 1 and c 2 can be adapted along the evolutionary loop over t
a ;
a combination of different methods could enable a better convergence at the end of the evolutionary loop (e.g., PSO+Simulated annealing [18], PSO+Nelder–Mead [17]).
The challenge of all these improvements is to reduce the required number of evaluations of f(x) and to increase the algorithm efficiency, but they are out of the scope of this paper and can be found in the extensive literature related to optimization. The reader can easily find websites where some authors give the associated codes written in various programming languages. The reader should keep in mind that the performance of a metaheuristic algorithm strongly depends on the problem. Indeed, each algorithm performs differently on different problems. Its performance (computation time and the success of the method) depends on the topological properties of the fitness function F [51]. Statistical analysis of the realizations of the algorithm is the only way to access the performances, the properties of F being a priori unknown. Therefore, N
r realizations of the same algorithm help to check the stability of this collaborative random search method.
